Overall, we show that increasing daylength is a monotonic driver of net productivity pervasive across all ranges of metabolic parameters (Fig. 2). Relatively abrupt changes in daylength, as caused by escape or entry into resonance locking, could therefore be among the triggers for the global oxidation events. In this respect, our proposed mechanism is similar to that of other abrupt events that cause imbalances in the global pO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
